Chapter 7: The Cost of a Tug

The silence of the sunken city was a lie. It wasn’t an absence of sound, but a compression of it, a weight of millennia-deep water now vanished but still pressing on the eardrums. Elara moved through the skeletal avenues of the metropolis, the Lens of Unseeing a cold, circular weight against her chest, secured inside her coat. It felt like carrying a hole in reality. Anya’s voice had been a filament in her mind, guiding her here, but it had grown thin, staticky, as if the very act of retrieving the Lens had stretched their connection across a gulf too wide.

“The entity knows you have it,” Anya’s words were faint, fraying at the edges. “It felt the artifact’s removal from its… curation. You have tugged the thread. It will tug back.”

Elara’s boots crunched on ossified coral that had grown over a tramcar. “Let it. I’m getting used to the fear.”

“This won’t be fear, child. This will be a correction.”

The correction began not with a scream, but with a sigh. A long, weary exhalation that seemed to come from the city itself, from the rusted girders and the faceless statues. The air, already stale, grew thick with the scent of ozone and old meat. Then, the pressure changed. Not around her, but inside. In the vault of her own skull.

It started as a migraine behind her eyes—a brilliant, painful star. Then the star exploded, and she was no longer in the sunken city.

