She was vast. She was hungry. She was a consciousness stretched across the silent places between galaxies, a pattern of thought that knew only one verb: consume. But not for destruction. For… completion. To fill a silence so absolute it was a screaming vacuum in the soul. She—It—reached out with perceptions that were not sight, not sound, but a direct tasting of the essence of things.

And there, below, was a spark. A tiny, warm, noisy cluster of sparks. Haven’s Rest.

Elara tried to shut her eyes, but she had no eyes. She was the entity. She felt its relentless, driving need, a loneliness so profound it had curdled into a cosmic appetite. It didn’t hate the town. It was drawn to it, as a freezing man is drawn to a flame, even if he must swallow it to feel its warmth.

She experienced the descent not as a fall, but as a focusing. The infinite consciousness poured itself into a single, terrible point of attention above the town. She felt the moment of contact—not an impact, but an unfolding. The entity’s presence bloomed over Haven’s Rest like a flower made of shadow and static, and its petals were made of screaming faces that were all, horribly, her own.

